{
  "response": "# Registration Form Accessibility Testing Plan\n\n> **For Claude:** Use a11y-planner protocol. Review with a11y-critic after testing plan execution.  \n> **Compliance target:** WCAG 2.2 AA  \n> **Users who need accessibility:** Screen reader users, keyboard-only users, low vision users, cognitive accessibility users  \n> **Assistive technologies:** NVDA Windows, JAWS Windows, VoiceOver macOS, keyboard-only users  \n\n**Feature:** Accessibility testing plan for an 8-field healthcare patient portal registration form with blur validation, submit validation, inline errors, summary banner, and password visibility toggle.  \n**Risk Level:** Medium  \n**Component/Page Type:** Multi-section form with validation and dynamic error messaging  \n\n---\n\n## Scope & Context\n\nThis plan covers testing for a React + React Hook Form registration form used at the entry point of a healthcare patient portal. Because this is a healthcare onboarding surface, failures are not just technical defects: inaccessible validation can block patients from creating an account.\n\nThe plan is not claiming the implementation is accessible. It defines how QA should verify accessibility consistently before production. The highest-risk areas are:\n\n- Field labels and required-state communication\n- Blur-triggered inline validation\n- Submit-time summary error banner\n- `aria-describedby` error associations\n- `aria-invalid` state updates\n- Keyboard order through two form sections\n- Screen reader form mode behavior\n- Password visibility toggle focus behavior\n\nThe form has two sections:\n\n1. Personal Information\n   - First name\n   - Last name\n   - Date of birth\n   - Phone\n\n2. Account Setup\n   - Email\n   - Password\n   - Confirm password\n   - Terms acceptance checkbox\n\nValidation fires:\n\n- On blur for individual fields\n- On submit for full-form validation\n\nWCAG grounding:\n\n- WCAG 1.3.1 Info and Relationships\n- WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color\n- WCAG 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum\n- WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast\n- WCAG 2.1.1 Keyboard\n- WCAG 2.4.3 Focus Order\n- WCAG 2.4.7 Focus Visible\n- WCAG 2.4.11 Focus Not Obscured\n- WCAG 2.5.8 Target Size Minimum\n- WCAG 3.3.1 Error Identification\n- WCAG 3.3.2 Labels or Instructions\n- WCAG 3.3.3 Error Suggestion\n- WCAG 3.3.7 Redundant Entry\n- WCAG 3.3.8 Accessible Authentication\n- WCAG 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n- WCAG 4.1.3 Status Messages\n\n---\n\n## Semantic Structure Plan\n\nThe form should be tested as a single semantic form with two grouped sections. QA should verify the rendered DOM, not only visual appearance.\n\nExpected structure:\n\n```html\n<main id=\"main-content\">\n  <h1>Register for patient portal</h1>\n\n  <form novalidate>\n    <fieldset>\n      <legend>Personal Information</legend>\n\n      [First name label + input + hint/error]\n      [Last name label + input + hint/error]\n      [Date of birth label + input + hint/error]\n      [Phone label + input + hint/error]\n    </fieldset>\n\n    <fieldset>\n      <legend>Account Setup</legend>\n\n      [Email label + input + hint/error]\n      [Password label + input + show password button + hint/error]\n      [Confirm password label + input + hint/error]\n      [Terms checkbox label + hint/error]\n    </fieldset>\n\n    [Submit error summary banner]\n    <button type=\"submit\">Create account</button>\n  </form>\n</main>\n```\n\nRequired semantic checks:\n\n| Element | Expected Result | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Page title | One clear `h1` describing registration | 2.4.6 Headings and Labels |\n| Form sections | `fieldset` and `legend` group Personal Information and Account Setup | 1.3.1 Info and Relationships |\n| Inputs | Every input has a visible `<label for>` association | 1.3.1, 3.3.2 |\n| Required state | Required state is communicated visually and programmatically | 1.3.1, 3.3.2, 4.1.2 |\n| Error text | Inline error appears near its field and is referenced by `aria-describedby` | 1.3.1, 3.3.1 |\n| Summary banner | Failed submit creates a programmatic alert/status and visible summary | 3.3.1, 4.1.3 |\n\nDo not accept `title` as an accessible name. Do not accept `aria-label` as the primary label if a visible label is missing. A visible label is preferred for all fields.\n\n---\n\n## Interaction Pattern Design\n\n### Interactive Elements Table\n\n| Widget | APG / Native Pattern | Keyboard Model | ARIA / HTML Attributes | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Text inputs | Native HTML text input | Tab focuses field; typing edits value | `<label for>`, `required` or `aria-required`, `aria-invalid`, `aria-describedby`, `autocomplete` | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 3.3.2, 4.1.2 |\n| Date of birth input | Native text/date input depending implementation | Tab focuses field; typing or date control interaction works by keyboard | Label, format hint via `aria-describedby`, `autocomplete=\"bday\"` if applicable | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 3.3.2 |\n| Phone input | Native tel input | Tab focuses field; typing edits value | `type=\"tel\"`, label, hint/error via `aria-describedby`, `autocomplete=\"tel\"` | 1.3.1, 3.3.2 |\n| Email input | Native email input | Tab focuses field; typing edits value | `type=\"email\"`, `autocomplete=\"email\"`, label, error reference | 1.3.1, 3.3.2, 4.1.2 |\n| Password inputs | Native password/text input | Tab focuses field; typing edits value | `autocomplete=\"new-password\"`, label, `aria-describedby` for requirements/errors | 1.3.1, 3.3.2, 3.3.8 |\n| Show password toggle | APG Button / Toggle Button pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/ | Tab focuses button; Enter/Space toggles visibility | Native `button`; use `aria-pressed` if state is \u201cshown/hidden\u201d | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Terms checkbox | Native checkbox | Tab focuses checkbox; Space toggles checked state | Native checkbox, label, required state, error via `aria-describedby` | 1.3.1, 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Submit button | Native button | Tab focuses button; Enter/Space submits | Native `button type=\"submit\"` | 2.1.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Submit error summary | Status / alert pattern | On failed submit, focus moves to banner | `role=\"alert\"` or alert container, `tabindex=\"-1\"` if focused | 2.4.3, 3.3.1, 4.1.3 |\n\n### Password Toggle Requirements\n\nThe \u201cShow password\u201d control must be tested as an interactive toggle, not as decorative text.\n\nExpected behavior:\n\n- It is a native button.\n- It has an accessible name such as \u201cShow password\u201d when hidden and \u201cHide password\u201d when visible, or a stable name with `aria-pressed`.\n- Enter and Space both activate it.\n- Focus remains on the toggle after activation unless the implementation intentionally restores focus to the password field.\n- Focus must not jump to the top of the page.\n- The password field context must remain understandable to screen reader users.\n\nWCAG citations: 2.1.1 Keyboard, 2.4.3 Focus Order, 4.1.2 Name Role Value, 3.3.8 Accessible Authentication.\n\n---\n\n## Focus Management Plan\n\nExpected keyboard order must match visual order:\n\n1. Skip link, if present\n2. First name\n3. Last name\n4. Date of birth\n5. Phone\n6. Email\n7. Password\n8. Show password toggle\n9. Confirm password\n10. Terms acceptance checkbox\n11. Submit button\n\nIf the summary error banner receives focus after failed submit, then the temporary order after submit is:\n\n1. Submit button activates\n2. Focus moves to summary error banner\n3. Tab moves to first invalid field link in banner, if links are included, or to first invalid field after the banner\n4. Activating an error summary link moves focus to the corresponding invalid field\n\nFocus rules:\n\n- Blur validation must not unexpectedly move focus.\n- Submit validation may move focus to the summary banner.\n- If summary links are used, each link must target and focus the related field.\n- Focus indicators must be visible on all fields, checkbox, password toggle, summary links, and submit button.\n- Sticky headers or banners must not obscure the focused summary or focused field. WCAG 2.4.11.\n- At 200% zoom and narrow viewport widths, focus order must remain logical and no field should become unreachable.\n\n---\n\n## State Communication Design\n\n### State Communication Table\n\n| State | Visual Indicator | Programmatic Indicator | ARIA / HTML Attribute | WCAG Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Required field | Red asterisk plus visible required text or legend note | Required state exposed to AT | Prefer native `required`; `aria-required=\"true\"` acceptable if used consistently | 1.3.1, 3.3.2, 4.1.2 |\n| Invalid field after blur | Red border, error icon/text below field | Field marked invalid and error associated | `aria-invalid=\"true\"` and `aria-describedby=\"[hint-id] [error-id]\"` | 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Valid field | Default border, no error text | `aria-invalid` absent or false | No stale error ID in `aria-describedby` | 4.1.2 |\n| Error summary after submit | Banner at top with heading and list of errors | Alert/status and focus target | `role=\"alert\"` and `tabindex=\"-1\"` if focused | 3.3.1, 4.1.3, 2.4.3 |\n| Password hidden | Button says \u201cShow password\u201d or unpressed toggle | Toggle state conveyed | `aria-pressed=\"false\"` if using toggle button model | 4.1.2 |\n| Password visible | Button says \u201cHide password\u201d or pressed toggle | Toggle state conveyed | `aria-pressed=\"true\"` if using toggle button model | 4.1.2 |\n| Terms unchecked invalid | Checkbox visually marked; error text shown | Checkbox invalid and described by error | `aria-invalid=\"true\"`, `aria-describedby=\"[error-id]\"` | 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 4.1.2 |\n| Submit pending, if applicable | Spinner and disabled submit | Busy/disabled state exposed | `aria-busy=\"true\"` on form region or native `disabled` on button | 4.1.2, 4.1.3 |\n\nImportant boundary: inline blur errors should be associated with fields through `aria-describedby`. Do not put `role=\"alert\"` on every field error in a repeating pattern unless there is a deliberate announcement strategy. One submit-time summary alert is safer and less noisy.\n\n---\n\n## Automated Testing Setup\n\nPlaywright + axe-core are already in CI. The testing plan should add form-specific coverage instead of a generic \u201crun axe\u201d step.\n\n### Axe-Core Rule IDs To Include\n\nRun axe on these states:\n\n- Initial empty form\n- Each field after blur validation error\n- Full form after failed submit\n- Password visible state\n- Terms unchecked submit error state\n- 200% zoom or narrow viewport equivalent, if supported in CI\n\nRelevant axe rules:\n\n| Rule ID | Why It Matters |\n|---|---|\n| `label` | Detects form controls without accessible labels |\n| `label-content-name-mismatch` | Detects visible label mismatch with accessible name, relevant for voice control |\n| `aria-required-attr` | Ensures ARIA roles with required attributes have them |\n| `aria-valid-attr` | Detects invalid ARIA attributes |\n| `aria-valid-attr-value` | Detects invalid ARIA values |\n| `aria-allowed-attr` | Detects ARIA attributes used on unsupported roles/elements |\n| `color-contrast` | Detects insufficient text contrast, including error text |\n| `autocomplete-valid` | Checks valid autocomplete tokens for personal/account fields |\n| `button-name` | Ensures password toggle and submit button have accessible names |\n| `form-field-multiple-labels` | Detects conflicting label associations |\n| `aria-input-field-name` | Helps catch named input-like ARIA widgets if custom controls appear |\n\nAxe does not prove that blur errors are announced correctly, that focus order is logical, or that NVDA Forms Mode reads errors in context. Those require manual and Playwright keyboard tests.\n\n---\n\n## Playwright Assertion Plan\n\nQA should verify rendered DOM state, not just screenshots.\n\nMinimum assertions:\n\n- Each field has a visible label and computed accessible name.\n- Each required field has required state exposed.\n- On blur with invalid empty value:\n  - Field has `aria-invalid=\"true\"`.\n  - Field has `aria-describedby`.\n  - The ID referenced by `aria-describedby` exists in the DOM.\n  - The referenced element contains the visible error message.\n- When the error clears:\n  - `aria-invalid` is removed or set to false.\n  - Stale error IDs are removed from `aria-describedby`.\n- On failed submit:\n  - Summary banner appears.\n  - Banner has `role=\"alert\"` or equivalent alert semantics.\n  - Focus moves to the banner or to a deterministic first-error target.\n  - Banner lists all invalid fields.\n  - Error summary links, if present, move focus to the correct field.\n- Password toggle:\n  - Is a button.\n  - Has an accessible name.\n  - Enter and Space activate it.\n  - State updates via text change or `aria-pressed`.\n  - Focus does not jump to the page top.\n- Terms checkbox:\n  - Space toggles checked state.\n  - Invalid state is associated with its error text.\n\n---\n\n## Manual Keyboard Runbook\n\nUse this runbook for every build candidate.\n\n### Test 1: Initial Tab Order\n\n1. Load the registration page.\n2. Press Tab from the browser address/content start.\n3. Confirm focus order:\n\n   First name \u2192 Last name \u2192 Date of birth \u2192 Phone \u2192 Email \u2192 Password \u2192 Show password \u2192 Confirm password \u2192 Terms acceptance checkbox \u2192 Submit button.\n\n4. Confirm each focused element has a visible focus indicator.\n5. Confirm focus is not hidden behind sticky headers or banners.\n6. Press Shift+Tab from Submit and confirm reverse order is logical.\n\nPass criteria:\n\n- All 8 fields, password toggle, checkbox, and submit are reachable.\n- Focus order matches the visual layout.\n- Focus indicator is visible for every interactive element.\n- No keyboard trap occurs.\n\nWCAG: 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.11.\n\n### Test 2: Blur Validation\n\nFor each required field:\n\n1. Tab to the field.\n2. Leave it empty.\n3. Tab away.\n4. Confirm inline error appears below the field.\n5. Confirm field has `aria-invalid=\"true\"`.\n6. Confirm field\u2019s `aria-describedby` references the visible error text.\n7. Type a valid value.\n8. Tab away again.\n9. Confirm error clears and invalid state is removed or false.\n\nPass criteria:\n\n- Error appears only after blur, not while typing.\n- Error text is specific and actionable.\n- Error is programmatically associated with the field.\n- No stale error remains after correction.\n\nWCAG: 1.3.1, 3.3.1, 3.3.2, 3.3.3, 4.1.2.\n\n### Test 3: Submit Error Summary\n\n1. Load a fresh form.\n2. Leave all fields empty.\n3. Tab to Submit.\n4. Press Enter.\n5. Confirm summary error banner appears at top of form.\n6. Confirm focus moves to the banner or deterministic first invalid field, per implementation decision.\n7. Confirm banner lists all invalid fields.\n8. If banner entries are links, activate each one and confirm focus moves to the related field.\n\nPass criteria:\n\n- Summary is announced as a status/error.\n- Focus movement is predictable.\n- Summary and inline field errors agree.\n- Error links target the correct fields.\n\nWCAG: 2.4.3, 3.3.1, 3.3.3, 4.1.3.\n\n### Test 4: Password Toggle\n\n1. Tab to Password.\n2. Enter a sample password.\n3. Tab to Show password.\n4. Press Space.\n5. Confirm password becomes visible.\n6. Confirm focus remains on the toggle or returns to the password field intentionally.\n7. Press Enter.\n8. Confirm password becomes hidden again.\n9. Confirm accessible state/name changes appropriately.\n\nPass criteria:\n\n- Toggle is keyboard operable.\n- Toggle has button semantics.\n- State is exposed through button text or `aria-pressed`.\n- Focus does not jump to the top or leave the password area.\n\nWCAG: 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 3.3.8, 4.1.2.\n\n---\n\n## Screen Reader Runbook\n\nQA team has no screen reader experience, so NVDA should be the primary screen reader test because it is free and common on Windows. JAWS and VoiceOver should be smoke-tested after NVDA passes.\n\n### NVDA Setup\n\n1. Open the form in Chrome or Edge on Windows.\n2. Start NVDA.\n3. Use Tab for form navigation.\n4. Use NVDA Forms Mode behavior naturally. If needed, press `F` to move between form fields.\n5. Do not rely only on browse-mode reading; form mode behavior is required for this fixture.\n\n### NVDA Form Mode Test\n\nFor each field:\n\n1. Press `F` or Tab to the field.\n2. Confirm NVDA announces:\n   - Field label\n   - Field type\n   - Required state, if exposed\n   - Current value, if any\n   - Error message after invalid blur\n\nExpected examples:\n\n- \u201cFirst name, edit, required\u201d\n- After blur error: \u201cFirst name, edit, invalid entry, First name is required\u201d\n- \u201cTerms acceptance, checkbox, not checked, required\u201d\n\nExact phrasing may vary by browser and screen reader. The pass condition is not exact text matching; it is whether label, role, state, and error are available in context.\n\n### NVDA Error Announcement Test\n\n1. Focus First name.\n2. Leave it empty.\n3. Tab away.\n4. Confirm the inline error is available when returning to the field.\n5. Repeat for all fields.\n6. Submit empty form.\n7. Confirm summary banner is announced or receives focus and can be read immediately.\n8. Confirm each error can be reached from summary or by tabbing to fields.\n\nPass criteria:\n\n- Labels are not silent.\n- Errors are not visually-only.\n- `aria-describedby` content is read with the field.\n- Summary banner is announced on submit.\n- There is not a flood of repeated alert announcements from every field.\n\n### JAWS and VoiceOver Smoke Tests\n\nAfter NVDA passes:\n\n- JAWS Windows: repeat one valid path and one failed submit path.\n- VoiceOver macOS Safari: verify labels, password toggle, field errors, summary banner, and focus order.\n\nResidual risk: without experienced screen reader testers, QA may miss nuanced verbosity or timing issues. That is why a11y-critic review remains a required checkpoint.\n\n---\n\n## Visual Regression Plan\n\nCapture screenshots for these states:\n\n1. Initial form default state\n2. Each field focused\n3. Each field invalid after blur\n4. Password hidden state\n5. Password visible state\n6. Terms checkbox invalid state\n7. Full submit error summary banner\n8. 200% zoom layout\n9. Narrow viewport layout\n10. High contrast or forced colors mode, if test environment supports it\n\nVisual acceptance criteria:\n\n- Normal text contrast is at least 4.5:1.\n- Large text contrast is at least 3:1.\n- Error borders, focus rings, and checkbox boundaries meet 3:1 non-text contrast.\n- Error state is not communicated by red alone: it also includes text and/or icon.\n- Required asterisk is not the only required indicator.\n- Focus indicator is clearly visible and not clipped.\n- All targets are at least 24x24 CSS pixels; 44x44 is preferred for healthcare entry flows.\n\nWCAG: 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.11, 2.4.7, 2.5.8.\n\n---\n\n## Test Prioritization And Execution Order\n\nBecause the deadline is 3 weeks, execute in this order:\n\n1. Automated axe-core and DOM assertions in CI\n2. Playwright keyboard order and ARIA state tests\n3. Manual keyboard runbook\n4. NVDA form mode runbook\n5. Visual regression for focus/error states\n6. JAWS and VoiceOver smoke tests\n7. a11y-critic review of results and implementation evidence\n\nIf time is constrained, do not skip NVDA form mode. That is the highest-value manual test for this feature.\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\nThe form passes accessibility testing only if all of the following are true:\n\n- Axe-core has no violations for the tested form states.\n- Every input has a visible label and correct accessible name.\n- Required state is exposed programmatically and visually.\n- Tab order is exactly: first name, last name, date of birth, phone, email, password, show password, confirm password, terms checkbox, submit.\n- Every field error is linked through `aria-describedby`.\n- Every invalid field receives `aria-invalid=\"true\"` after validation.\n- Corrected fields clear invalid state and stale error references.\n- Failed submit displays a summary banner with all current errors.\n- Failed submit moves focus predictably to the banner or first invalid field.\n- Summary banner uses `role=\"alert\"` or equivalent announcement behavior.\n- Password toggle is a keyboard-operable button.\n- Password toggle exposes its state through text or `aria-pressed`.\n- Focus does not jump to the top after password toggle activation.\n- NVDA Forms Mode reads label, role, required state, and error context for each field.\n- Error states are not communicated by color alone.\n- Focus indicators are visible in default, error, zoomed, and narrow viewport states.\n- No functionality is lost at 200% zoom or narrow viewport width.\n- DOM verification confirms ARIA attributes are on the correct elements.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Tasks\n\n### Task 1: Automated Axe And DOM Tests\n\n**Files:**\n\n- Playwright accessibility spec for registration form\n- Existing CI axe-core integration\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Run axe on initial, blur-error, submit-error, password-visible, and terms-error states.\n- Assert rule coverage for `label`, `label-content-name-mismatch`, `aria-required-attr`, `color-contrast`, and `autocomplete-valid`.\n- Verify `aria-invalid`, `aria-describedby`, and alert banner placement in rendered DOM.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** a11y-critic should verify rule selection, tested states, and DOM assertion completeness.\n\n### Task 2: Keyboard Navigation Tests\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Tab through all fields and controls in expected order.\n- Shift+Tab reverses correctly.\n- Enter/Space activate submit, checkbox, and password toggle.\n- No unexpected focus jump on blur validation.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** a11y-critic should focus on WCAG 2.1.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, and focus behavior after validation.\n\n### Task 3: Error Announcement Tests\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Trigger blur error on each field.\n- Verify field has `aria-invalid=\"true\"`.\n- Verify `aria-describedby` references the visible error.\n- Submit empty form and verify summary banner behavior.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** a11y-critic should verify inline errors are associated with fields and submit summary is not duplicative or noisy.\n\n### Task 4: Screen Reader Runbooks\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- NVDA full runbook.\n- JAWS smoke test.\n- VoiceOver smoke test.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** a11y-critic should review screen reader findings, especially any mismatch between visual error text and announced context.\n\n### Task 5: Visual Regression\n\n**Tests:**\n\n- Default, focus, error, password visible, summary banner, zoom, and narrow viewport screenshots.\n- Contrast checks for text, error states, focus rings, and controls.\n\n**Review checkpoint:** a11y-critic should verify color is not the sole indicator and focus remains visible.\n\n---\n\n## a11y-Critic Review Checkpoints\n\n| Checkpoint | After Task | Focus Areas |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Automated tests | Axe rule coverage, DOM verification, tested states |\n| 2 | Keyboard tests | Tab order, password toggle, submit behavior, no keyboard trap |\n| 3 | Error tests | `aria-invalid`, `aria-describedby`, summary alert, focus movement |\n| 4 | Screen reader runbook | NVDA Forms Mode, label/error context, announcement timing |\n| 5 | Visual regression | Focus indicators, contrast, non-color error indicators, zoom behavior |\n\n---\n\n## Failure Modes This Plan Prevents\n\n- Visually present labels that are not programmatically associated\n- Red-only required or error indicators\n- Inline errors that appear visually but are not read with the field\n- Per-field alert regions causing repeated noisy announcements\n- Submit summary banner that appears but is never announced\n- Password visibility toggle that changes state silently\n- Focus jumping to the top after password toggle activation\n- QA saying \u201cscreen reader tested\u201d without testing NVDA Forms Mode\n- Axe passing while keyboard order or announcements still fail\n\n## References\n\n- WAI-ARIA APG Button Pattern: https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/button/\n- WCAG 2.2 Quick Reference: https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG22/quickref/\n- axe-core Rules: https://dequeuniversity.com/rules/axe/",
